05163nam a22009255i 9780520939608DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20072006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209396087 a10.1525/97805209396082doi  a(DE-B1597)520140  a(OCoLC)77835604  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aTX911.3.C8bS54 2007eb 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a647.940682221 aSherman, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClass Acts :bService and Inequality in Luxury Hotels /cRachel Sherman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (373 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Luxury Service And The New Economy -- t1. “Better Than Your Mother”: The Luxury Product -- t2. Managing Autonomy -- t3. Games, Control, And Skill -- t4. Recasting Hierarchy -- t5. Reciprocity, Relationship, And Revenge -- t6. Producing Entitlement -- tConclusion: Class, Culture, And The Service Theater -- tAppendix A: Methods -- tAppendix B: Hotel Organization -- tAppendix C: Jobs, Wages, And Nonmanagerial Workers In Each Hotel: 2000–2001 -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this lively study, Rachel Sherman goes behind the scenes in two urban luxury hotels to give a nuanced picture of the workers who care for and cater to wealthy guests by providing seemingly unlimited personal attention. Drawing on in-depth interviews and extended ethnographic research in a range of hotel jobs, including concierge, bellperson, and housekeeper, Sherman gives an insightful analysis of what exactly luxury service consists of, how managers organize its production, and how workers and guests negotiate the inequality between them. She finds that workers employ a variety of practices to assert a powerful sense of self, including playing games, comparing themselves to other workers and guests, and forming meaningful and reciprocal relations with guests. Through their contact with hotel staff, guests learn how to behave in the luxury environment and come to see themselves as deserving of luxury consumption. These practices, Sherman argues, help make class inequality seem normal, something to be taken for granted. Throughout, Class Acts sheds new light on the complex relationship between class and service work, an increasingly relevant topic in light of the growing economic inequality in the United States that underlies luxury consumption.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aHospitality industryxCustomer servicesxUnited States. 0aHospitality industryxCustomer serviceszUnited States. 0aHotel managementxUnited States. 0aHotel managementzUnited States. 0aLuxuriesxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aLuxuriesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSocial classesxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aamerica.  abehind the scenes.  abellperson.  aclass differences.  aconcierge.  aconsumer society.  acultural studies.  ademographic study.  aeconomic inequality.  aethnographers.  aethnographic research.  ahotel jobs.  ahotel managers.  ahotel staff.  ahotel workers.  ahousekeepers.  aluxury consumption.  aluxury hotels.  aluxury service.  anonfiction study.  anonfiction.  aservice industry.  asocial inequality.  asocial relationships.  aunited states.  aurban hotels.  awealthy guests.  aworkplace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093960840uhtt